{"Do family physicians know the costs of medical care?": [["Do family physicians know the costs of medical care?", "Family physicians often lack detailed knowledge about specific cost structures related to various medical services due to focusing primarily on clinical practice rather than reimbursement systems. Research indicates variability among practices; some may receive formal education on health economics but such information might vary significantly depending upon continuing educational opportunities available locally. Therefore, while many family doctors understand general principles like insurance coverage policies impacting patient out-of-pocket expenses, comprehensive understanding of pricing models across different providers remains inconsistent amongst practitioners. Enhancing transparency through more accessible databases could potentially increase awareness and inform better decision-making around referrals and treatments based on overall affordability considerations."], ["Do family physicians know the costs of medical care?", "Family physicians often lack detailed knowledge about the specific cost structures of various diagnostic tests, treatments, medications, and hospital procedures due to varying insurance policies, regional differences in pricing models, and the focus on clinical practice rather than finance. Studies suggest that while some primary care providers might receive general information through continuing education programs or health systems initiatives aimed at increasing physician awareness around patient affordability issues, many still struggle to provide accurate estimates when discussing options with patients who inquire about out-of-pocket expenses related to their recommended course of action. This gap highlights the need for more comprehensive resources or integrated billing/coding support directly accessible to front-line clinicians to better inform shared decision-making processes centered on patient welfare and economic cons